We recommended and Management agreed to:
3. Require the Office Treasurer to prepare and submit the Report of Check Issued for all payments made;
4. Enjoin the AIAS to maintain the required registries to ensure that disbursements will not exceed their corresponding obligations, allotments or appropriations;
5. Instruct the Office of the AIAS to issue and use disbursement vouchers for all the money claims against the funds of CGT; and
6. Advise the City Accountant and Treasurer to coordinate and adopt a system and procedures, to ensure prompt and efficient submission of the required reports and disbursement vouchers to the Audit Team.

We recommended and management agreed that the GSO and CAO, in view of the gaps observed and raised in audit to consider the:

a. formalization of CGT’s Inspectorate Team to facilitate the inspection of PPE deliveries, to promote accountability over the process; Identify the members of the CGT Inspectorate Team for various transactions including the PPE deliveries.

b. recording of semi-expendable items in the respective Inventory accounts and eliminating the same from the PPE balance and the corresponding accumulated depreciation. Further, issue the corresponding ICS to all the end-users of the semi-expendable items;

c. development of the Information Technology System to interconnect the Property Management module of the AIASO and CGSO; and to adopt the systematize number coding of PPE items;

d. immediate reconciliation of the PPE records between that of AIASO and the CGSO. It is to be emphasized that under the guidelines, each of the office mentioned, is directed to keep its own records/property ledgers/cards to record accurate balances of PPE accounts;

e. maintenance of Real Property records with complete specification substantiated by complete details as to its acquisition date, TCT number, and other necessary information;

f. review of the correct reckoning date and estimated useful life of the asset is used in computing depreciation. Moreover, see to it that whenever changes as to the useful life and net realizable value of assets are made, the Schedule of Depreciation is updated accordingly;

g. conduct the periodic Physical Count of PPE items by directing concerned offices to perform the comprehensive inventory taking of items under their responsibility; and

h. drawing of necessary adjusting journal entries corresponding the overstatements and understatements contained in Tables I, J, and M above, and necessary disclosures relative to the Property, Plant and Equipment to facilitate better understanding of the same, and in accord with transparency and accountability.

We recommended and management agreed, through the personnel concerned to consider the:

a. review of the existing accountability and reporting lines with respect to the Local Road Networks, to promote accountability over the processes;

b. determination by the GSO and that of the City Treasurer’s Office (CTO) of those road lots covered by TCTs, Deeds of Donation, and Usufruct Agreements, and retrieve the appropriate documents relative thereto. Ensure that original copies of these documents are safely kept and secured in the CTO’s vault, and that second copies are to be made available in the GSO’s office. Also, for accounting purposes, to provide the same set of documents to the City Accountant’s Office (CAO) for the eventual recording of corresponding road lots in the CGT’s books;

c. updating of the local road map, and ascertain those that are under public domain. Road lots classified under, and/or are previously on public domain, necessitate proper disclosures in the Notes to the Financial Statements;

d. preparation and furnishing by the City Engineering Office (CEO) of the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects to the CAO and that of the GSO for reference and identification purposes;

e. proper tagging and assignment of corresponding Road Network I.D.s by the CEO and in coordination with the concerned offices, for every project to prior to undertaking the same, and in the preparation of the corresponding Program of Works to ensure that complete description as regards the road network projects and their components are provided, in keeping with the LRAMS Manual promulgated by the DILG;

h. drawing of necessary adjusting journal entries corresponding the overstatements and understatements, and necessary disclosures relative to the Road Networks to facilitate better understanding of the same, and in accord with transparency and accountability.

We recommend and the management agreed to:

f. draw separate financial information and reports as regards the operations of the LEEs, as if these were independent segments, in keeping with the standards on segment reporting;

g. provide adequate disclosures in the Notes to Financial Statements pertaining to these economic enterprises;

i. make a comprehensive assessment of the performance of the local economic enterprises, particularly the public market operations, such assessment to include actual inspection and inventory of occupants vis-à-vis issued business permits and contracts of lease as awarded by the City Government;

j. articulate the results of such comprehensive assessment to a formal report to be rendered to the Local Chief Executive, the results to show information to include but not limited to (1) the results of financial operations; (2) violations committed by the stall occupants, as reported, and corresponding actions taken by the City Government; and (3) other reportable conditions;

We recommended and Management agreed, and in view of the inadequacy of manpower complement of the City Government to:
Re-evaluate the status of the City Government’s projects, activities and programs. Ascertain the constraints that were seen to have deterred the supposed timely implementation thereof. Formally document in the Risk Registry, if any, the identified impediments and/or limitations and have them timely updated as ready reference for future undertakings;
Program of works concerning that of projects under the Special Education Fund be prepared by the CPDO given that there are engineers lodged in the said office who have technical skills to do the work to unload the tasks laden in the CEO;
Provide additional fund for job order engineers to increase their daily wage rate for a more attractive pay and to compete with the average daily wage rate for the said profession. Also, annually provide additional budget for the additional plantilla positions for technical personnel; and
Have a gradual manning complement to be lodged at the General Services Office for small repairs and maintenance.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Re-assess the level of targeted collections for the current year with reference to the previous year’s actual collections. Intensify the collection of local revenue through the imposition of proper taxes/fees based on the adopted local revenue code whenever warranted;
Revisit the 2011 Local Revenue Code, align the same, if warranted, with that of the recently passed tax laws; and determine if amendments thereto are needed;
Conduct massive information drive on the City Government’s revenue collection, projects, programs and activities to encourage and gain continuous support from the community; and
Communicate with the Registry of Deeds regarding the requirements for auction on delinquent properties to facilitate and hasten the public sale.

Further, we also recommended, which Management likewise agreed to enhance the administration and collection of Real Property Taxes through adopting a more realistic and current valuation of properties and intensive collection of delinquent accounts. Moreover, carefully prepare a detailed study of the proposals, with corresponding support schedules justifying the need to have the schedule of assessment values updated.

We recommended that the Management:

Address the Accounting Department to:

Maintain subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network;

Prepare/maintain the Local Road Network Ledger Card (Annex D);

Prepare a lapsing schedule for the computation of the depreciation for each component at the end of the year; and

Disclose the total network system in the Notes to the Financial Statements (Annex B).

Require the General Services Office to:

Maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map;

Keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components (Annex E);

Prepare the Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network System (Annex C); and

Render a Report on Local Road Network of the LGU at the end of the accounting period (Annex A).

We recommended that the Management:
Address the Accounting Department to:
Maintain subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network;
Prepare/maintain the Local Road Network Ledger Card (Annex I);
Prepare a lapsing schedule for the computation of the depreciation for each component at the end of the year; and
Disclose the total network system in the Notes to the Financial Statements (Annex G).
Require the General Services Office to:
Maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map;
Keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components (Annex J);
Prepare the Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network System; (Annex H) and
Render a Report on Local Road Network of the LGU at the end of the accounting period (Annex F).
Direct the City Engineering Office to provide the accounting office and the general services office with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects.
